VALUES
(43, 15, 1, 24, 2, 21, 21, 'I am the true vine', 'Vine Imagery in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the imagery of the vine, where John presents Jesus as the ''true vine'' and Jeremiah refers to Israel as a ''noble vine.'' Both passages emphasize the relationship between the vine and its caretaker, illustrating themes of growth and degeneration.', 'theme', 0.839, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 15, 1, 23, 27, 2, 3, 'vine', 'Vineyard Imagery Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a vineyard, with John referring to Jesus as the true vine and Isaiah depicting the vineyard as being cared for by the Lord. This connection highlights the nurturing aspect of God in relation to His people.', 'theme', 0.776, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 15, 1, 46, 3, 9, 9, 'my Father is the husbandman', 'Connection of Vine and Husbandry', 'Both passages emphasize the role of God as the husbandman, highlighting the relationship between God and His people. John 15:1 introduces God as the true vine, while 1 Corinthians 3:9 refers to believers as God''s husbandry, illustrating a shared theme of cultivation and care.', 'theme', 0.587, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 15, 1, 23, 60, 21, 21, NULL, 'Vine and Branch Imagery', 'This connection highlights the imagery of the vine and the branch, where Jesus identifies himself as the true vine and Isaiah refers to the branch of God''s planting. Both passages emphasize the relationship between God and his people, illustrating a divine cultivation for righteousness and glory.', 'theme', 0.58, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 15, 1, 19, 80, 8, 19, 'I am the true vine', 'Vine Imagery Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a vine, with John identifying Jesus as the ''true vine'' and Psalms describing Israel as a vine brought from Egypt. This connection highlights the significance of the vine as a symbol of God''s people and their relationship with Him.', 'theme', 0.552, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 15, 1, 43, 6, 55, 55, 'I am the true vine', 'Connection of Life and Sustenance', 'This connection highlights the theme of sustenance in both passages. The ''true vine'' represents a source of spiritual nourishment, while ''flesh'' and ''blood'' signify the physical sustenance provided by Christ.', 'theme', 0.51, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 15, 1, 24, 12, 10, 10, NULL, 'Vineyard Imagery Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a vineyard, with John presenting Jesus as the true vine and Jeremiah lamenting the destruction of God''s vineyard by unfaithful leaders. This connection highlights the significance of care and stewardship in relation to God''s people.', 'theme', 0.46099999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 15, 2, 40, 3, 10, 10, NULL, 'Fruitfulness and Judgment Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of bearing fruit. John 15:2 speaks of branches being purged to produce more fruit, while Matthew 3:10 warns that trees not bearing good fruit will be cut down. This connection highlights the consequences of unfruitfulness.', 'theme', 0.839, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 15, 2, 58, 12, 10, 11, 'fruit', 'Connection of Fruitfulness and Chastening', 'Both passages emphasize the process of producing fruit through discipline. John 15:2 speaks of purging branches to yield more fruit, while Hebrews 12:10-11 discusses chastening that ultimately leads to the ''peaceable fruit of righteousness.'' This connection highlights the theme of growth through trials.', 'theme', 0.762, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 15, 2, 40, 15, 13, 13, 'Every branch in me that beareth not fruit', 'Fruitfulness and Divine Judgment', 'Both passages emphasize the idea of divine judgment on plants or branches that do not bear fruit. John 15:2 speaks of branches being taken away if they do not bear fruit, while Matthew 15:13 mentions plants not planted by the Father being uprooted.', 'theme', 0.643, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 15, 2, 66, 3, 19, 19, 'purgeth it, that it may bring forth more fruit', 'Connection of Purging and Chastening', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine correction. Both passages emphasize the necessity of being pruned or chastened to produce greater spiritual fruit.', 'theme', 0.5589999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 15, 2, 43, 15, 8, 8, NULL, 'Fruitfulness and Discipleship', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of bearing fruit. The first passage discusses purging branches to increase fruitfulness, while the second highlights that bearing much fruit glorifies the Father and signifies true discipleship.', 'theme', 0.538, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 15, 2, 42, 13, 7, 9, 'beareth not fruit', 'Fruitfulness and Judgment', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of bearing fruit. John 15:2 discusses purging branches to increase fruitfulness, while Luke 13:7-9 addresses the judgment of a fruitless fig tree. This connection highlights the theme of divine expectation regarding fruitfulness.', 'theme', 0.51, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 15, 2, 58, 6, 7, 8, 'beareth not fruit', 'Connection of Fruitfulness and Judgment', 'Both passages emphasize the consequences of fruitfulness. John 15:2 discusses branches that bear fruit being purged for more fruit, while Hebrews 6:7-8 contrasts fruitful earth with that which bears thorns, leading to rejection.', 'theme', 0.43999999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 15, 3, 43, 17, 17, 17, 'the word', 'Connection of Cleansing and Truth', 'Both passages emphasize the transformative power of God''s word. John 15:3 speaks of being ''clean through the word,'' while John 17:17 highlights the sanctifying effect of ''thy word'' as truth.', 'theme', 0.657, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 15, 3, 49, 5, 26, 26, 'clean through the word', 'Cleansing Through the Word', 'This connection highlights the theme of cleansing through the word. Both passages emphasize the transformative power of the word in making one clean or sanctified.', 'theme', 0.6359999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 15, 3, 60, 1, 22, 22, 'clean through the word', 'Purification and Love Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of purification through obedience to the truth. John 15:3 speaks of being clean through the word, while 1 Peter 1:22 discusses purifying souls in obeying the truth, linking the concepts of spiritual cleanliness and love for one another.', 'theme', 0.5449999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 15, 3, 43, 13, 10, 10, 'ye are clean', 'Connection of Cleansing Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of being ''clean.'' In John 15:3, Jesus states that his words make the disciples clean, while in John 13:10, he affirms their cleanliness, indicating a spiritual cleansing that is essential for their relationship with him.', 'theme', 0.46799999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 15, 4, 62, 2, 6, 6, 'abide in me', 'Abiding in Christ', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''abide'' in relation to one''s relationship with Christ. John 15:4 highlights the necessity of abiding in Jesus to bear fruit, while 1 John 2:6 connects abiding with walking as He walked.', 'theme', 0.9789999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 15, 4, 48, 2, 20, 20, 'abide in me, and I in you', 'Connection of Abiding in Christ', 'Both passages emphasize the idea of Christ living in believers. John 15:4 speaks of abiding in Christ, while Galatians 2:20 expresses that Christ lives in the believer, highlighting a mutual indwelling.', 'theme', 0.825, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 15, 4, 43, 8, 31, 31, 'abide in me', 'Connection of Abiding and Continuing', 'This connection highlights the importance of remaining in Jesus to be fruitful and to truly follow Him. Both passages emphasize the necessity of ongoing relationship and commitment to His teachings.', 'theme', 0.7829999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 15, 4, 63, 1, 9, 9, 'abide in me', 'Abiding in Christ''s Doctrine', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of abiding, whether in Christ or in His doctrine. This connection highlights that true relationship with God is contingent upon remaining in Him and His teachings.', 'theme', 0.734, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 15, 4, 43, 6, 56, 56, 'abide in me, and I in you', 'Connection of Abiding in Christ', 'Both passages emphasize the mutual indwelling of believers and Christ. The concept of ''dwelling'' in John 6:56 parallels the idea of ''abide'' in John 15:4, highlighting the necessity of a close relationship for spiritual vitality.', 'theme', 0.706, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 15, 4, 50, 1, 11, 11, 'abide in me', 'Connection of Righteousness and Abiding', 'This connection highlights the importance of abiding in Christ to produce the fruits of righteousness. Both passages emphasize that spiritual fruitfulness is dependent on a relationship with Jesus.', 'theme', 0.552, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 15, 4, 62, 2, 24, 28, 'abide in me', 'Abiding in Christ', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of abiding in Christ for spiritual vitality and assurance of eternal life. The call to ''abide in me'' in John 15:4 parallels the encouragement to let what was heard from the beginning ''abide in you'' in 1 John 2:24.', 'theme', 0.524, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 15, 5, 43, 15, 16, 16, 'bringeth forth much fruit', 'Connection of Fruitfulness in Christ', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of bearing fruit as a result of one''s relationship with Christ. The first verse highlights that without Him, one can do nothing, while the second assures that believers are chosen to bring forth fruit that remains.', 'theme', 1.0, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 15, 5, 50, 4, 13, 13, 'without me ye can do nothing', 'Connection of Strength in Christ', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of Christ for accomplishing tasks. John 15:5 highlights that without Christ, one can do nothing, while Philippians 4:13 asserts that strength comes through Christ.', 'theme', 1.0, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 15, 5, 51, 1, 10, 10, 'bringeth forth much fruit', 'Fruitfulness in Christian Life', 'This connection highlights the theme of being fruitful in one''s actions. Both passages emphasize the importance of abiding in Christ to produce good works and knowledge of God.', 'theme', 1.0, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 15, 5, 48, 5, 22, 22, 'bringeth forth much fruit', 'Connection of Fruit and Abiding', 'This connection highlights the theme of producing fruit through a relationship with Christ. John emphasizes that abiding in Him leads to much fruit, while Galatians lists the specific fruits of the Spirit that result from such a relationship.', 'theme', 0.986, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
